{
  "doc_id": "8566",
  "text": "Assisted reproductive technologies (ARTs), including in vitro fertilization (IVF), are increasingly used for infertility treatment in humans. More than 6 million children have been conceived through IVF and other ARTs [CITATION_1] . Although ARTs are thought to be safe, multiple studies suggest that children and adolescents conceived by IVF are at increased risk of metabolic diseases, due to elevated blood pressure, fasting glucose, and peripheral body fat [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In particular, young adults conceived by IVF display reduced insulin sensitivity and may be more susceptible to the deleterious metabolic consequence of obesogenic environment [CITATION_4] . Animal studies further confirm the influence of IVF on metabolism at later developmental stages. IVF alters the composition of lipid in mouse fetal liver, and adult mice conceived by IVF display increased fasting glucose levels and impaired glucose tolerance [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The metabolome in adult fat and liver is also altered by IVF, and metabolites enriched in steroidogenesis and pyrimidine metabolism are elevated by IVF [CITATION_7] .",
